\section*{RECOGNIZING TACHYCARDIA}

Tachycardia is defined as a heart rate greater than what is considered normal for a child's age. Like bradycardia, tachycardia can be life-threatening if it compromises the heart's ability to perfuse effectively. When the heart beats too quickly, there is a shortened relaxation phase. This causes two main problems: the ventricles are unable to fill completely, so cardiac output is lowered; and the coronary arteries receive less blood, so supply to the heart is decreased.
There are several kinds of tachycardia, and they can be difficult to differentiate in children on ECG due to the elevated heart rate.

